nd":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1150–1208":"about 1150–1208","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1192–1242":"1192–1242","1211–1233":"1211–1233","1109–1188":"1109–1188","about 1150":"about 1150","1242":"1242","1150":"1150","1192":"1192","1215":"1215","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","1188":"1188","1155":"1155","about 1189":"about 1189","after 1188":"after 1188","ABT 1192":"about 1192","1208":"1208","1109":"1109","Coberley, Gloucestershire":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Coberley, Cheltenham, Gloucestershire, England":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Coberley, Gloucestershire, England":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Berkeley II was born about 1150, in Coberley, Gloucestershire, England as the son of Great Chamberlain I William de Berkeley. He married Dionysia Turberville about 1189. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1208, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1150–1208":"umbes 1150–1208","1150–1208":"1150–1208","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1192–1242":"1192–1242","1211–1233":"1211–1233","1109–1188":"1109–1188","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1242":"1242","1150":"1150","1192":"1192","1215":"1215","123